executeToolCall -> InternalToolExecutionResult:
Given information about the state of the current assistant-customer conversation: in a loop over a list of tools, identifies (and, if available, executes) the tool's callback, observes the execution of said callback, and stores the execution results of each callback to be run.

toolContext: Context in which callbacks should be run.

summary_q:
The method `createRequest()` takes in two parameters `prompt` and `stream`. Based on the message type of `prompt`, the method generates different responses which are outputted to `stream`. 

Check if the message in `prompt` is from User or System. If so, extract text from message as `content`. If message if from user and contains media, convert media into `content`. Return a chat completion message with the content and the message type (user or system). 

If the message in `prompt` is from the Assistant, check if it contains tool calls. If so, return a chat completion message with the original message, and the list of tools specified in the original message. 

If the message in `prompt` is from the Tool, return a chat completion message with the responses from the specified tools. 

If the message in `prompt` is not from User, System, Assistant, or Tool, thrown an illegal argument exception as the message type is unsupported.

summary_q:
The method `headCellRangeList()` identifies cells that need to be merged - a.k.a. those that contains the same string (`headName`). The method iterates over each column (the first for loop). For each row in the column, the method checks if consecutive columns in the same row contain the same string `headName` and records the last column in which the same value occurs. 

The method then checks if for consecutive rows, the values from the current column `i` to the previously identified last column `k` are identical. The last consecutive row for which this is true is recorded as the last row. 

If there are any consecutive rows/columns that needs to be merged, the method returns the ranges of the rows and columns that need to be merged.

summary_q: This code iterates through indices i in a list of Excel Heads. A hashset is used to record already set column row pairs. A list of names for each head is retrieved using getHeadNameList. A nested loop iterates through indices j in this list of names. If i and j are in the set of already set pairs, the current iteration is skipped. Two additional nested loops iterate 1. through the columns k past i, checking if the head name in this column at row j is equal to the head name at column i and row j, and if the pair is not already set. If both are true, then this value k is stored as the last column, and the pair is marked as set. If not, then the loop is broken. 2. through the rows k past j, and then within this loop through the columns l starting from i to the previously stored value of k. The same condition as before is checked using l and the new k. If true, the pair l and k are marked as set but using a temp range which prevents their addition from interfering with the loop. If false, the loop iterating variable k is broken. If the loop iterating variable l finishes without reaching this break, the value k is stored as the last row and the temporarily stored set of set pairs is added to the existing set. After both of these loops, if the values of last column and last row have changed, then the cell range of j to the last row and i to the last column are added to a cell range list.

summary_q: This code takes in a list of documents and a set of options. First, it checks if an embedding model is provided. Then the code checks for the presence of transformer options. A JSON node parser is configured using the transformer options, provided or default. Then the code checks for retriever options. A retriever is configured using the provided or default options. The non-null provided documents are mapped to a list of IDs. The options, configurations, and list of IDs are compiled into an upsert pipeline request. This request is sent to the REST API endpoint /api/v1/indices/pipeline. If the response is null or has a status other than success, an error is thrown. The response is retrieved using another endpoint, and an error is again thrown if null or has a non-success status.

summary_q: The function adds a transaction to a database with threading and locks based on a RunnableConfig config and a Checkpoint checkpoint. The function returns a RunnableConfig. There are checkpoints stored alongside each transaction which represent stages of the transaction. When a client session is started, it puts a lock on the thread. If the transaction has been logged before in the database, the document and checkpoints for that checkpoint are saved into local variables. If the transaction has been logged and the checkpoint id parameter has previously been logged, the function logs a new checkpoint to the transaction in that document under that id and returns the config parameter. If there are no logged checkpoints, the function will create a new list of checkpoints and add the current one to it; else, it appends it to the existing list of checkpoints. A new RunnableConfig is created for the new checkpoint id (since it has not existed before), which is returned.

summary_q:
This method is for error handling. It first checks the type of the body (an HttpRequestNode type object), and if the type is NONE it breaks. 

If the type is RAW_TEXT, it checks if the size of the body is not equal to 1 and prints an error message that the body must contain exactly one item. It then creates a string called rawText by replacing the item in body with the state. Then it sets the header content/media type to plain text, the body to raw text, and breaks.

If the type is JSON, it checks if the size of the body is not equal to 1 and prints an error message that the body must contain exactly one item. It then creates a string called jsonTemplate by replacing the item in body with the state and creates a new object called jsonObject. It attempts to parse the JSON body by creating a new ObjectMapper which tries to read the jsonTemplate string, but if this fails if throws an error that says "Failed to parse JSON body." If it's able to parse the body, it sets the header content type to APPLICATION_JSON and sets the body value to jsonObject.

The method completes a similar process for body types X_WWW_FORM_URLENCODED, FORM_DATA and BINARY, where it checks to see if the body satisfies any requirements of the data type (for example, binary must also contain exactly one item), replaces the first item in body with the state, and sets the header content type and the body value.

If the body type doesn't match any of these cases, the default is to print an error message that says "unsupported body type."
